# This is an EXAMPLE file. It shows what your private keys file looks like.
#
# When you connect a tool that needs a key (Claude will walk you through this
# in Lesson 4), you'll make a real file called ".env" and put your keys in it.
#
# To do that: copy this file, rename the copy to ".env", and replace the
# example values with your real keys. Your real ".env" file stays private
# and is never shared (the .gitignore file makes sure of that).
#
# You don't need to do anything with this file right now. It's just here
# so you have a template when you're ready.

# Example: an OpenAI / ChatGPT key would look like this
# OPENAI_API_KEY=your-key-goes-here

# Example: a key for an email or other service
# SOME_SERVICE_API_KEY=your-key-goes-here
